related ? 

Is something like "Add Resource Dump" better?
Ack

Is there a design doc for Resource dump ? 
Can you explain what it is and how it differs from System Dump?

I have added Dhruv to the Reviewers list.

@dhruv, do you want to answer this?

The resource dump is a non-disruptive dump created by HOST, the BMC just initiate or offload when it is ready. Where as a system dump is disruptive dump involving a server reboot. the reboot is orchestrated by the BMC and the content is collected by the host.
I think we need a design document for these different types of dumps explaining them and then in the commit msg we can point to that.
Dhruv, Do we have some design document explaining about the different types of dump?
This is my first question.  "resource" doesn't properly describe what the dump is, what it's used for, or how someone would execute one.
Here is a documentation on the resource dump https://www.ibm.com/support/pages/how-initiate-resource-dump-hmc-enhanced-gui

Can you add some of this to the commit message? 
I still think a design document on the different dumps is needed

Ed, Resource dump is : where user tries to get the dump of a specific resource(say some hardware data).
To achieve this: User sends some command which executes on the restricted hypervisor.
Hypervisor gets the data to the BMC which gets offloaded to the client.

How is it different from the System dump:
System dump where we gets the data of the whole hypervisor memory,
System dump is a disruptive in nature while Resource dumps are non disruptive.

More info is at following link:
https://www.ibm.com/support/pages/how-initiate-resource-dump-hmc-enhanced-gui
I know unlikely to break but can you run the validator ?
Ack

This commit presumes that "resource dump" is a common term, which it is not.  Please provide information on WHY this change is valuable and what this change would be used for in a general application.

This is useful in a sense if redfish client wants a debug data for a certain resource they just gets the param(which resource) which will be understand by the hypervisor and hypervisor collects the data and give it to the BMC(pldm-phosphor-debug-collector).
This is the first instance of these, but OEM log types likely should have the same rules as OEM schemas, in that they impose the same requirements and concerns a schemas.

DMTF suggested that we can extend the enums, in a way that in the standard enum value we would have OEM as value and then we would have property named OEMPropertyName.

Eg: In this case we have the DiagnosticDataType which is having the value as OEM, If we have the value as OEM then we have to use the property OEMDiagnosticDataType with any other string.

I am not getting why we need to provide a schema for the same.

Do we really need to define a new type? If the intent is to enable passing parameters as per https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/+/37355, can we encode that as "key1=value1;key2=value2;..." for the "System" type and parse the same, if it exists?

You mean to say for system, we would be passing "System" for OEMDiagnosticDataType and for resource it should be something like:

'{"DiagnosticDataType":"OEM", "OEMDiagnosticDataType":"com.ibm.Dump.Create.CreateParameters.VSPString:<vspString>;com.ibm.Dump.Create.CreateParameters.Password:<password>"}'

If so, yes instead of doing Resource_<vspstring>_<password>, we could do like how you suggested that avoids the definition of a new type.

Thanks for this, Deepak.

Ed, I think we discussed the same in the discord, You suggested that we should use the GUID, Are you suggesting the backend should provide the GUID or the bmcweb should create the GUID and have the mapping in the bmcweb between the bmcweb generated GUID and the ID returns from the backend.
Why does this need to be explicitly specified in each case? The previous to_lower_copy() should work?
Ack

It is because, the dumpType would be sent in either as system or bmc.
The resource check falls here in this method above. Hence, used this dumpPath to store the respective dump entry paths
we don't need to explicitly tell about Resource dump service here.
Ack

Instead of passing the dump type, Can we have the logic where we can send the d-bus interface to get all the objects implementing that interface.
I know we have the specific dbus interface for the dump types..
https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/tree/master/xyz/openbmc_project/Dump/Entry
we need to use name based on type?

Why is Resource dump under com.ibm.Dump.Entry. but system dump is under xyz.openbmc_project.Dump.Entry. ?

Based on the discussions earlier it is found that 
System dump - a common scenario any openbmc users can use this
Resource dump - an IBM specific dump type
More description needed about what a "Resource dump" is.  "resource" has special meaning in redfish, and I don't believe you're using the vernacular correctly in this case.

ACK.
https://gerrit.openbmc-project.xyz/c/openbmc/docs/+/41508/5/designs/dump-manager.md is the design document for this change. Here the resource is the hosts resource, which is identified using a specific resource id.
50/72 please.
Ack

This would imply that we can send schemaless data through bmcweb, which is actively discouraged by both Redfish and bmcweb.  Please structure this data appropriately so that these endpoints can be reused by others.

Yes. This is IBM specific use-case. Seems like we can put this under a IBM specific compiler flag ?

The DiagnosticDataType is OEM, and we are using OEMDiagnosticDataType field to pass the system specific values as an input to the dump creation

This is not how redfish describes this, and there is nothing in redfish that's snake case, especially upper snake case.  Please follow the example of other similar things in terms of naming this.

This also implies that we're supporting system-specific naming of these things, which seems wrong.  We should have a fixed set of these that's known at compile time.
